{"version":1,"ops":[{"type":1,"author":{"id":"e6c152d440109efdc7afc4e9ac4ac193043f8f68"},"timestamp":1464945034,"metadata":{"github-id":"MDU6SXNzdWUxNTgzMjM3NDI=","github-url":"https://github.com/letoram/arcan/issues/95","origin":"github"},"title":"(platform/egl-dri) VT switching problems","message":"The egl-dri platform do not currently handle VT switching gracefully (or really, at all, it crashes). There are a number of reasons why this task is one of the worst pieces of legacy in Linux.\n\nOne of them is that it is an inherently race-condition prone thing and you do not know when you are coming back or what you are coming back to. GPUs, Audio Devices, Input Devices can all be lost, added or moved without you knowing. This is made worse with the whole slew of 'Kits/logind/login manager/seat/session infestation and equally over-complicated bullshit. \n\nAnother is that you are not always in a safe-state for releasing resources because they are being used in a locked state, like a complex compute shader with readbacks for something that stalls (the halting problem again) longer than the timeout for the hand-over signals to be dealt with, or synchronization with a dynamic refresh display that stalls.\n\nThe action plan for this is as follows:\n1. Shmif - Migration support. This feature will allow frameservers to transparently migrate connections to either a new key/path or connection-loop if and then migrate shmif- segment state over to the new connection.\n1. launch_target_external. This is still missing in the egl-dri platform implementation, but there used to be support for saving the current display state to a local buffer, releasing device resources and then rebuilding (in the SDL platform) but there are some exotic corner cases (vids with a GPU-only backed store). This also requires the running appl to handle _display_state(reset) event, but that's mostly finished in durden/display.lua, which others can just re-use.\n\n3.If the running appl- tracks window etc. state in a persistent way, we can then simply shut the whole thing down on VT switch, or trigger [1] by pulling the dead-man switch in the shmif and then re-expose connection points when we are back.","files":null}]}